4.b. Examination of possible association between average delay and proportion of cancelled flights.

The visualization below suggests that as the average delay increases for a particular day, so does the number of cancelled flights. This makes intuitive sense to anyone with experience flying!

# Compare proportion of cancelled flights to average delay for each day
summary <- flights.1 %>% group_by(day_of_year) %>%
  summarize(
    num_cancelled = sum(is.na(dep_delay) & is.na(arr_delay)),
    prop_cancelled = mean(is.na(dep_delay) & is.na(arr_delay)),
    ave_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
# Visualize comparison of proportion of cancelled flights to average delay
ggplot(summary, aes(x = ave_delay, y = prop_cancelled)) + geom_point(alpha = .6) + 
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

  1. The sort argument to count() sorts the output in descending order of n. It provides a quick way to see not just the max and min, but the several highest and lowest occurring counts. This could give you ideas for next steps in an analysis (e.g.what do the several highest count or several lowest count groups have in common?).

R for Data Science Exercise 10.5

  1. You can tell an object is a tibble by printing it (it returns the classification a tibble), or by using class(). You can also tell its a tibble when printed in the console, because tibbles are easier to read than data frames (they do not wrap columns around and print them below). They also name the type of data in each column, which data frames do not.

  2. The data frame defaults could be frustrating because a typo in subsetting a column name wouldnt throw an error so you could easily make a mistake without knowing it. Also, it could be frustrating that the type of object being returned changes. When youre working with a tibble, the results will always also be a tibble, so you dont have to consider the class of object as you work.

df <- data.frame(abc = 1, xyz = "a")
df$x # Does not distinguish x from xyz, so this code returns the data from column xyz
## [1] a
## Levels: a
tb <- tibble(abc = 1, xyz = "a")
tb$x # Does distinguish x from xyz, so this code returns an error
## Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: 'x'.
## NULL
df[, "xyz"] # Returns contents of column xyz as a factor
## [1] a
## Levels: a
tb[, "xyz"] # Returns contents of column xyz as a tibble
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   xyz  
##   <chr>
## 1 a
df[, c("abc", "xyz")] # Returns a data frame with contents of column xyz as a factor
##   abc xyz
## 1   1   a
tb[, c("abc", "xyz")] # Returns a tibble with contents of column xyz as a character
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##     abc xyz  
##   <dbl> <chr>
## 1  1.00 a
  1. You can extract a reference variable named as an object from a tibble as coded here:
vari <- "carrier"

  1. The option n_extra controls how many additional column names are printed at the footer of a tibble.

R for Data Science Exercise 12.3.3

  1. The code fails because the column names 1999 and 2000 are non-syntactic and therefore must be surrounded by backticks.

  2. Spreading the given tibble fails because Phillip Woods has two different values for age, presumably because there are two different people in this data set named Phillip Woods. You could solve this problem by adding a new column that distinguishes Phillip Woods #1 from Phillip Woods #2. See code below:

people <- tribble(
  ~name,             ~key,    ~value,
  #-----------------|--------|------
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       45,
  "Phillip Woods",   "height",   186,
  "Phillip Woods",   "age",       50,
  "Jessica Cordero", "age",       37,
  "Jessica Cordero", "height",   156
)

people %>% mutate(ID = c(1,1,2,1,1)) %>% spread(key, value)

  1. The variables are pregnant (Y/N), sex (M/F), and some value (probably count). The sex variable needs to be gathered:
preg <- tribble(
  ~pregnant, ~male, ~female,
  "yes",     NA,    10,
  "no",      20,    12
)

preg %>% gather("male", "female", key = "sex", value = "n")

R for Data Science Exercise 12.4.3

  1. When sep is a character vector, extra controls what happens when there are too many pieces and fill controls what happens when there arent enough pieces to fill out the new columns. See below for examples:
# extra = "warn" (this is the default) gives a warning message and drops extra values
# extra = "drop" does the same thing without a warning
tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e,f,g", "h,i,j")) %>% 
  separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"))
## Warning: Too many values at 1 locations: 2
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
## * <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 d     e     f    
## 3 h     i     j
# extra = "merge" only splits at most the number of times as there are new columns and puts whatever is left over into the last column
tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e,f,g", "h,i,j")) %>% 
  separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"), extra = "merge")
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
## * <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 d     e     f,g  
## 3 h     i     j
# fill = "warn" (default) gives a warning and fills with NA from the right
# fill = "right" does the same thing without a warning
tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e", "f,g,i")) %>% 
  separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"))
## Warning: Too few values at 1 locations: 2
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
## * <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 d     e     <NA> 
## 3 f     g     i
# fill = "left" fills with NA from the left
tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e", "f,g,i")) %>% 
  separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"), fill = "left")
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
## * <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 <NA>  d     e    
## 3 f     g     i
  1. The default for remove in unite() and separate() is TRUE. This removes from the output tibble the original columns that were transformed by the function. You would set it to FALSE if you wanted both the original columns and the transformed ones in your output tibble, as in the example below:
table3 %>% 
  separate(rate, into = c("cases", "population"), remove = FALSE)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
